<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06118016 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06118016 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FINANCE; LOAN; PRODUCT; COMPANY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Boston food fight pitting some restaurants against Amercian Express Co.escalated Friday when Visa International admitted it footed legal expenses sothe restaurants could challenge the credit-card fees rival American Expresscharges merchants.;    Last month, the Boston restaurant owners threatened toboycott American Express unless the company lowered the fees it assessed themfor handling American Express card bills. The boycott threat resulted in alowering of fees to some restaurants, effective June 1.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  VISA BACKED AMERICAN EXPRESS REVOLT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Visa acknowledged Friday it arranged to pay the legal fees so therestaurants would be properly represented in their dispute with AmericanExpress.;    &quot;We felt it would be in their interests to have experienced legalcounsel,&quot; said Gregory Holmes, a spokesman for San Mateo-based Visa. &quot;Theytold us they were not in a financial position to pay for it.&quot; So, Holmesadded, Visa arranged to pay for the services of Hale andamp; Doerr, a Boston lawfirm.;    &quot;We're shocked that Visa would do something like this,&quot; saidLawrence Kurlander, American Express senior vice president for public affairsand communications. &quot;They did it surreptitiously. It's clear Visa wanted tohide the fact that they were behind this.&quot;;    American Express is &quot;exploringits options,&quot; Kurlander added. &quot;This was a major manipulation of the press, ofmerchants and of the consuming public.&quot;;    Holmes said Visa viewed theassistance as part of its merchant-support program.;    &quot;Providing support invarious forms is ongoing for us,&quot; he said. &quot;The decision by those restaurantsto voice their dissatisfaction (with American Express) was entirely theirown.&quot;;    Holmes said he doubted if Visa had paid legal bills for merchants inthe past and said he could not answer a hypothetical question about whetherthe credit-card membership association, the largest in the world, would do soin the future.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Chicago Tribune  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New York  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910427  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  298  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday April 27, 199100118016,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>